<author><name><![CDATA[kyuusaku]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-05-20T08:23:33-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-05-20T07:56:57-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7767&amp;p=78370#p78370</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7767&amp;p=78370#p78370"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[In 6502 asm, how big is a &quot;word&quot;?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7767&amp;p=78370#p78370"><![CDATA[
I have to agree that 6502 words are 8-bit. It has nothing to do with the ALU, nor holding an address; a word is technically not tied to any specific number of bits, it's a generic type that for most processors will be the external data bus and/or instruction width. Memory devices are frequently expressed as n x n-bit words where the width isn't even necessarily a power of 2. Early DRAM came in 1-bit words, so it would take 8 words in parallel to form a sufficient data bus for the 6502. Ancient mini computers may have like 50-bit words, but perhaps only 32-bit can be used for data leaving 18-bits for dedicated instruction encoding. This scheme far predates the 8086 but also fits the 8086 which has a 16-bit bus; reading a DWORD or double word thus denotes two 16-bit memory fetches. (Despite the 8088 having an 8-bit bus, the programming model is identical so they kept the notation.)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=20">kyuusaku</a> — Fri May 20, 2011 7:56 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
